post_cb({"bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_19755033_19755953_1": {"length": 20, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 7182}}, "n3337": {"so_19755033_19755953_1": {"length": 20, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 6926}}}, "19755033": {"ViewCount": "90", "Body": "<p>The question is as above; if I have, for example, <code>int* ptr = new int[10]</code> and after some operations with data <code>ptr</code> is set to, say, 2nd, 3rd 5th or last element, will the call <code>delete[] ptr</code> be the correct one? Can't find it in the manual. </p>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "19755049", "Title": "Can the argument of delete[] operator point to non-first element of an array?", "CreationDate": "2013-11-03T16:14:50.900", "Id": "19755033", "CommentCount": "3", "LastEditDate": "2015-08-26T18:00:55.763", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "4370109", "LastActivityDate": "2015-08-26T18:00:55.763", "Score": "1", "OwnerUserId": "858590", "Tags": "<c++><delete-operator>", "AnswerCount": "3"}, "19755953": {"PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_19755033_19755953_0\">Can't find it in the manual</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>C++11 3.7.4.2/3 says </p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_19755033_19755953_1\">behavior is undefined if the value supplied to operator <code>delete[](void*)</code> in the standard library is not one of the values returned by a previous invocation of either <code>operator new[](std::size_t)</code> or <code>operator new[](std::size_t, const std::nothrow_t&amp;)</code> in the standard library</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2013-11-03T17:47:24.857", "Id": "19755953", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2013-11-03T17:47:24.857", "ParentId": "19755033", "Score": "2", "OwnerUserId": "204847"}, "19755049": {"PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>No, the argument passed to the <code>delete[]</code> operator must point to the same address that was returned by <code>new[]</code></p>\n<p>(Assuming you haven't overloaded <code>delete[]</code> and <code>new[]</code> to do something crazy)</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2013-11-03T16:16:23.807", "Id": "19755049", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2013-11-03T16:16:23.807", "ParentId": "19755033", "Score": "5", "OwnerUserId": "168288"}, "19755081": {"PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>From the C++ reference manual <a href=\"http://www.cplusplus.com/reference/new/operator%20delete%5b%5d/\" rel=\"nofollow\">delete[]</a>: <em>Notice that an invalid value of ptr causes undefined behaviour.</em><br>\nBecause of this it is not recommended to manipulate the pointer to your allocated memory directly! </br></p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2013-11-03T16:18:20.520", "Id": "19755081", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2013-11-03T16:18:20.520", "ParentId": "19755033", "Score": "2", "OwnerUserId": "2878796"}});